-- Regression: Iron_ExprNode common layout assumption (runtime safety net).
--
-- **Motivating Incident.** Phase 65 AUDIT-01 rank 9 flagged
-- src/hir/hir_lower.c:109 for locally defining an Iron_ExprNode typedef
-- that assumed every expression AST type begins with
-- {Iron_Span span; Iron_NodeKind kind; struct Iron_Type *resolved_type;}.
-- If any expression type ever deviated from that prefix, the expr_type()
-- helper would silently read garbage for resolved_type and propagate
-- wrong types through HIR lowering — the class of bug that motivated
-- the whole v0.1.4-alpha Compiler Correctness milestone.
--
-- **Layout Diagram.**
--   Every expression AST type (Iron_IntLit, Iron_FloatLit, Iron_StringLit,
--   Iron_BoolLit, Iron_NullLit, Iron_Ident, Iron_BinaryExpr, Iron_UnaryExpr,
--   Iron_CallExpr, Iron_MethodCallExpr, Iron_FieldAccess, Iron_IndexExpr,
--   Iron_SliceExpr, Iron_LambdaExpr, Iron_HeapExpr, Iron_RcExpr,
--   Iron_ComptimeExpr, Iron_IsExpr, Iron_ConstructExpr, Iron_ArrayLit,
--   Iron_EnumConstruct, Iron_AwaitExpr, Iron_InterpString) must begin
--   with the exact prefix:
--     [Iron_Span span][Iron_NodeKind kind][struct Iron_Type *resolved_type]
--   Compile-time enforcement via _Static_assert in src/parser/ast.h
--   (PROT-01, Phase 66 Plan 01) is the primary defense. This fixture is
--   the runtime belt-and-braces: it funnels many concrete expression
--   kinds through HIR lowering's expr_type() so a wrong resolved_type
--   read surfaces as a type error or a runtime crash instead of silent
--   bad codegen.
--
-- **Fix Summary.** Plan 01 moved Iron_ExprNode to src/parser/ast.h and
-- added _Static_assert prefix enforcement on every expression type
-- (IRON_ASSERT_EXPR_PREFIX macro applied 23 times). This fixture is the
-- RUNTIME safety net that protects against a future refactor which
-- somehow bypasses the static asserts (e.g., conditional compilation,
-- a new expression type someone forgets to register, or a #pragma pack
-- change). If the compile-time checks ever miss a drift, a wrong
-- resolved_type read on any of the exercised kinds produces a visible
-- failure here. PROT-04 belt-and-braces runtime fixture, Phase 66 Plan
-- 03.
--
-- **Severity.** H. Protects HIR lowering's type propagation for every
-- Iron program — the common layout assumption is the foundation every
-- expression-kind switch relies on.

func add(x: Int, y: Int) -> Int {
    return x + y
}

object Pair {
    val a: Int
    val b: Int
}

func main() {
    -- Exercise a wide set of expression AST kinds. Each of these
    -- expressions flows through expr_type() during HIR lowering; if the
    -- Iron_ExprNode common prefix ever breaks for any concrete expression
    -- type, the resolved_type read on that kind will produce either a
    -- type error (caught by typecheck) or a wrong codegen (caught by
    -- the println interpolation below).
    val int_lit  = 42                    -- Iron_IntLit
    val str_lit  = "hello"               -- Iron_StringLit
    val bool_lit = true                  -- Iron_BoolLit
    val ident    = int_lit               -- Iron_Ident
    val binop    = int_lit + 1           -- Iron_BinaryExpr
    val unary    = -int_lit              -- Iron_UnaryExpr
    val call     = add(int_lit, 1)       -- Iron_CallExpr
    val pair     = Pair(int_lit, call)   -- Iron_CallExpr -> ObjectDecl construct
    val field    = pair.a                -- Iron_FieldAccess
    val arr      = [1, 2, 3]             -- Iron_ArrayLit
    val index    = arr[0]                -- Iron_IndexExpr
    val interp   = "value: {int_lit}"    -- Iron_InterpString

    println("int: {int_lit}")
    println("str: {str_lit}")
    println("bool: {bool_lit}")
    println("ident: {ident}")
    println("binop: {binop}")
    println("unary: {unary}")
    println("call: {call}")
    println("field: {field}")
    println("index: {index}")
    println(interp)
}
